    <p>Dear Seenivasan and Annamalai,<br>
      <br>
      Thank you Seenivasan for responding to the Section 13 IST
      questions. I have reviewed all twelve responses carefully. Before
      giving you the specific feedback, I want to first explain a
      pattern I am seeing that affects more than half of your answers —
      because correcting this pattern will make the second round of
      responses significantly more useful.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b><font size="4">On the IST reviewer's role — a clarification for
          the whole team</font></b><br>
      <br>
      In several responses, Seenivasan has answered the question 'what
      should SPINRISE do' instead of 'what does the current VB6 system
      do.' For example, IST-3 says 'OfferRateFlg should be controlled as
      a system parameter' and IST-5 says 'TCS threshold should be stored
      in a parameter table.' These are SPINRISE design recommendations,
      not IST answers.<br>
      <br>
      <b>The IST reviewer's role in the FSD process is to describe
        current, factual behaviour from field experience at customer
        sites.</b> The CEO and TL-Dev take those factual descriptions
      and make the SPINRISE design decisions. If an IST response says
      'should be' or 'recommended to be', that is a future-state
      opinion. <b>What I need is 'currently is' or 'at site X, this is
        how it works.'<br>
      </b><br>
      <b>This applies to IST-1, IST-3, IST-4, IST-5, and IST-8. I will
        address each specifically below.<br>
      </b><br>
      <br>
      <b>What is well answered and confirmed for the FSD</b><br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-6 (Mix Ratio):</b> Confirmed as applicable only for JW
      contract type. SPINRISE will make the Mix Ratio constraint
      contract-type-configurable so that future contract types can be
      added without code changes. Annamalai, update FSD Section 4 to
      confirm JW-only with a note that SPINRISE will make this
      configurable.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-7 (IG_INSBODT vs IG_BODT):</b> This is the best answer in
      the submission and provides genuinely valuable domain knowledge
      that is not visible in the FSD at all. IG_INSBODT is the two-step
      despatch path — Sale Order to Despatch Instruction to Goods Out —
      used when Sales or Planning must issue a formal internal
      instruction to Stores before goods move. IG_BODT is the one-step
      direct despatch path — Sale Order to Goods Out — where no Despatch
      Instruction is needed. Both paths are controlled by parameter
      settings. Annamalai, add this as Section 5.7 — Despatch Workflow:
      document both paths, state that SPINRISE must support both, and
      note that the controlling ig_param flag name is to be confirmed
      (see IST-7 follow-up below).<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-9 (Deletion vs Cancellation):</b> Confirmed correctly.
      Physical delete is permitted only when no downstream transactions
      (dispatch, invoice) exist. Once any transaction has been
      performed, cancellation (CANCELLED='Y') is the only permitted
      action. This aligns with the existing FSD delete guard. Annamalai,
      confirm in FSD Section 5.4 Workflow Rules that cancellation is the
      post-transaction action and physical delete guard checks both
      ig_bodt and ig_insbodt records before permitting deletion.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-11 (Multi-division): </b>Confirmed. A sale order is always
      division-specific. divcode is fixed at creation. SPINRISE does not
      need to support cross-division orders. This is a clean
      architectural confirmation. Annamalai, add this to FSD Section 3
      as a Field Rule for divcode.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-2 (Agent Code):</b> The Party Type reference (D1, D2, D5)
      is useful new domain knowledge not in the FSD. The agent mandatory
      rule is driven by Party Type classification, not a universal
      company or division parameter. Annamalai, add this to FSD Section
      4 Header Validations: Agent Code mandatory when customer party
      type falls within the configured types. However, Seenivasan, one
      addition is needed — which ig_param or MASTERLEN entry currently
      controls the party type list that requires agent code? Is
      AgentSelectFlag in Spinmod.bas the controlling flag, or is it
      something else?<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-10 (Report Footer) and IST-12 (Auto-mail): </b>Both are
      partially answered. Footer is confirmed as division-wise, and SMTP
      is confirmed as the email mechanism triggered during print or
      order confirmation. These are sufficient for now, but see the
      follow-up questions below.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b><font color="#ff0000">Responses that need re-answering —
          current state, not future recommendation</font></b><br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-1 (Credit Limit Override): </b>Your answer says credit
      limit override 'must not be permitted to all users.' That is a
      design recommendation for SPINRISE, not a description of the
      current system. What I need to know is: in the current VB6 ERP,
      which users can override a credit limit breach today? Is it
      controlled by the ulevel field in PP_Passwd? Is there a specific
      ulevel value that grants override permission? Has IST ever had to
      assist a customer in bypassing a credit limit, and how was that
      done? The FSD already documents that CRLimitLockFlg='N' allows a
      warning with Yes/No override and CRLimitLockFlg='Y' sends the
      order to an approval queue. Which of these two modes is currently
      used at most customer sites? That is the IST answer needed.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-3 (OfferRateFlg): </b>Your answer says it 'should be
      controlled as a system parameter.' It already is a system
      parameter in the current ERP — the FSD documents that OfferRateFlg
      is read from ig_param. What the question asks is: what is the
      actual ig_param column name? Which customers or divisions
      currently have it set to True? Is it used by specific product
      segments (e.g., fabric vs yarn) or specific customers only?
      Understanding who uses it today determines whether SPINRISE shows
      the Offer Rate and Discount columns for all users or only for
      specific divisions.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-4 (CSM Integration): </b>This is not a future system
      design question. The CSM REST API integration is already coded in
      frmcontract.frm today — the VB6 code calls GetApiResponse() with
      an endpoint URL read from CSM_API_Details table. The question asks
      whether this integration is live at any customer site right now.
      Is it? If yes, which customer site uses CSM integration currently?
      If it is not live at any site, please state that explicitly. That
      single factual answer determines whether SPINRISE is migrating an
      existing live integration or building something new. These have
      very different scopes.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-5 (TCS Threshold):</b> Your answer says the threshold
      'should be stored in a parameter table.' What I need to know is
      where it is CURRENTLY stored. Is the TCS threshold of Rs. 50 lakhs
      (the standard statutory threshold) hard-coded inside
      KSP_TCSAmountCheckLSales? Or does the SP read it from ig_param or
      a separate TCS configuration table? If it is hard-coded in the SP,
      that is a defect that SPINRISE must fix. If it is already in a
      table, name the table.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-8 (RateDeciPos):</b> Your answer says it should be
      configurable between 2 and 4 decimal places. That is a SPINRISE
      recommendation. What is the CURRENT standard value used at
      Kalsofte customer sites? Do all customers use the same precision,
      or do some divisions use 2 and others use 4? A simple query —
      SELECT divcode, RateDeciPos FROM ig_param — at any live customer
      site will answer this.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b>Follow-up additions needed from Seenivasan</b><br>
      <br>
      Beyond the five re-answers above, three short additions will
      complete the IST review:<br>
      <br>
      IST-7 follow-up: Which ig_param flag name controls whether the
      Despatch Instruction path (IG_INSBODT) or the Direct Despatch path
      (IG_BODT) is active? The FSD references IG_PARAM.DesInstr but this
      needs confirmation from IST.<br>
      <br>
      IST-10 follow-up: What specific fields does fr_RepFooter
      configure? Company address, authorised signatory name, bank
      details, terms and conditions? Which table stores the footer data
      — ig_repfoot or another table?<br>
      <br>
      IST-12 follow-up: Is CheckAutoMail currently active at any live
      customer site? Which ig_param flag is checked by CheckAutoMail()?<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b>For Annamalai — FSD updates to make immediately<br>
      </b><br>
      Do not wait for all IST responses before updating the FSD. The
      confirmed answers above generate specific FSD additions that can
      be written now:<br>
      <br>
      Section 4: Add JW Mix Ratio validation as confirmed. Add Agent
      mandatory rule based on Party Type classification.<br>
      <br>
      Section 5: Add Section 5.7 Despatch Workflow (IG_INSBODT vs
      IG_BODT as described above). Update Section 5.4 deletion guard to
      confirm both ig_bodt and ig_insbodt checks. Add multi-division:
      always division-specific.<br>
      <br>
      FSD Section 3: divcode is division-specific and fixed at order
      creation.<br>
      <br>
      Sections 1, 3, 7, and 8: Mark CSM integration, OfferRateFlg scope,
      TCS threshold storage, and RateDeciPos current values as [PENDING
      IST RESPONSE] so the FSD clearly shows what is still open.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b><font size="4">Overall</font></b><br>
      <br>
      Seenivasan, the IST-7 answer alone demonstrates that you have the
      domain knowledge this FSD needs. The despatch path distinction is
      the kind of field experience that no code analysis produces. Apply
      that same approach to the five re-answers above — describe what
      you have seen at customer sites, not what you think SPINRISE
      should do.<br>
      <br>
      The corrected responses and the three follow-up additions are all
      achievable today. Please revert by end of day.<br>
      <br>
      Regards,<br>
      T. Mani<br>
      <br>
      cc: TL-IST Palanivel, PM Saravanan</p>
